Hamiltons strikes out. We really wanna like this place but there's always something.  Today we walked over and got a table, wasn't very busy. Our bill was $40 already with just the 4 drinks. We would have stayed and drank more and probably ate eventually. Either way we felt insulted. I would understand if it was 2 ppl at a 4 top. Granted it was filling up a bit but as we were leaving there were at least 2-3 tables being cleaned. Someone just didn't want us sitting and drinking and taking in the day in their section I guess. Turn em and burn em I guess. Sorry Hamiltons but this isn't the experience we're looking for. Picture of said "drinking table" attached.

This is an awfully nice, very adult, bar and restaurant.  They do lunch, dinner, and brunch well--you can take your visiting relatives here. The clientele is mostly local and a few of us make the walk from other nabes to get there.  My interests aren't brunch, I'm a drinker.  You can join their mug club and get more suds for the same price as the non members get for buying a 16 oz pint.  It's worth it. The beer selection is a standout, and includes seasonal offerings and some fun local stuff, like Queens lager (when available).  You have a good choice of American micro brews.  Windsor Terrace is a family nabe, and the establishment is kid-friendly.  The menu includes the obligatory chicken bites and mac-and-cheese.  When you're done here you're a few steps from a great public library, or Greenwood playground if you want to burn off some calories.  It's a 3 minute walk from the F or G train at Ft. Hamilton Parkway.  If you're coming in from the city or the Slope, be on the front of the train, or vice versa if you're arriving from Deeper Brooklyn.

I've been to this restaurant tons of times. It is consistently good though a little pricey. I'm a person who usually can't finish a meal and ends up taking half of it home for leftovers. It's not the case at Hamiltons. So when I'm in the mood for a splurge I go. Their Portobello sandwich is the bomb and my husband is convinced they have the best burgers in our neck of the woods. Be warned, and this is why I gave it three stars instead of four and a half, that certain times of the day Hamiltons caters to Hipster parents and their unruly kids. And yes, I am a mom. My kid just doesn't run around the restaurant while I'm trying to eat. Because this neighborhood is changing this has been a common occurrence the past six or seven times I have been here. You can expect, during lunch and early dinner time, parents getting their glass of wine on and their kids being out of control in the restaurant. Sad because I will only order takeout from now on. It's not worth the babysitting you have to do as a patron.
